Meanwhile, in Syria, fighter jets from the U.S.-led coalition bombed oil installations and other facilities in territory controlled by the Islamic State  in eastern Syria for a second consecutive day, activists said today.

The strikes hit two oil areas in Deir el-Zour province a day after the United States and its Arab allies pummeled a dozen makeshift oil producing facilities in the same area near Syria's border with Iraq. 

The raids aim to cripple one of the terror group's primary sources of cash - black market oil sales that the U.S. says earn up to £2million a day. 

The Britain-based Syrian Observatory for Human Rights said the strikes overnight and early Friday hit the Tink oil field as well as the Qouriyeh oil-producing area in Deir el-Zour.  

